{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=August 2015}} {{Infobox Organization | image = [[File:Variable Energy Cyclotron Centre.svg|250px]] | image_size = | caption = [[Seal (device)|Seal]] of VECC | formation = 1977 | status = Operational | purpose = [[Nuclear research|Nuclear Research]] | headquarters = [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]], India | coords = {{coord|22.6010|88.4192}} | leader_title = Director | leader_name = Amitava Roy | name = Variable Energy Cyclotron Centre | abbreviation = VECC | parent_organisation = [[Department of Atomic Energy]] | website = {{URL|http://www.vecc.gov.in/}} }}
The '''Variable Energy Cyclotron Centre''' ('''VECC''') is a research and development unit of the [[Department of Atomic Energy (India)|Department of Atomic Energy]]. The VECC is located in [[Kolkata]], India and performs research in basic and applied nuclear sciences and development of latest accelerators. It has a collaboration with [[CERN|European Organization for Nuclear Research]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbni.ac.in/ci/44vecc.htm|title=Variable Energy Cyclotron Centre, Kolkata |publisher=Homi Bhabha National Institute |accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> The Centre houses a 224&nbsp;cm [[cyclotron]]—the first of its kind in India—which has been operational since 16 June 1977.<ref>{{cite book|last=Asoke Nath Mitra|title=India in the World of Physics: Then and Now|year=2009|publisher=Pearson Education India|isbn=9788131715796|page=318|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hRLPM6s7hWAC&pg=PA318&dq=Variable+Energy+Cyclotron+Centre+logo&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TQtUU5GsG83_rAfo3YCgDg&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Variable%20Energy%20Cyclotron%20Centre%20logo&f=false}}</ref> It provides [[proton]], [[deuteron]], [[alpha particle]] and heavy ion beams of various energies to other institutions.
The Centre consists of major facilities such as K130 Cyclotron, K500 Superconducting Cyclotron, Cyclone-30 Medical Cyclotron, RIB Facility, Computing Centre, Regional Radiation Medicine Centre and upcoming new Campus for proposed ANURIB project<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/science/New-nuke-physics-facility-planned-in-Kolkata/article20562349.ece |title=New nuke physics facility planned in Kolkata |access-date=20 Oct 2018 |newspaper=The Hindu Business Line}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/kolkata/laboratory-for-research-on-radioactive-ion-beams-soon/story-YvfiU7HbvXmuQFy0SLhEWJ.html |title=Laboratory for research on radioactive ion beams soon |date=17 Jun 2013 |access-date=20 Oct 2018 |publisher=Hindustan Times |author=Sudeshna Pal}}</ref> at New Town, Rajarhat. The ANURIB (Advanced National facility for Unstable & Rare-Isotope Beams) is planned facility, to be constructed in a collaboration with Canada-based research institute [[TRIUMF]].<ref>http://www.triumf.ca/headlines/workshops-conferences/expanding-partnerships-india</ref> ANURIB is going to conduct experiments of unstable & rare isotope beams.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/kolkata-to-house-asia-s-second-lab-to-study-supernova-conditions/1055235/0 | title=Kolkata to house Asia’s second lab to study supernova conditions | first=Madhuparna | last=Das | date=6 January 2013 | newspaper=The Indian Express | accessdate=30 May 2018 }}</ref>
